nigd Koninkrijk","Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1322–1360":"1322–1360","1322–1387":"1322–1387","1329–Male":"1329–Deceased","1331–Male":"1331–Deceased","1340–1406":"1340–1406","–Male":"Deceased","1337":"1337","about 1329":"about 1329","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1387":"1387","1331":"1331","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","about 1331":"about 1331","1406":"1406","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, England":"Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Langton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the many places called with Old English <i>lang</i> ‘long’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, such as Langton Hall in Kirkby in Ashfield (Nottinghamshire), Langton Lodge in Hendon (Middlesex), Langton (Yorkshire), East and West Langton (Leicestershire), Langton by Horncastle, Langton by Spilsby, and Langton by Wragby (all in Lincolnshire), and Lanton (Northumb). Compare   Lankton  ,   Lanton  , and   Longton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lanton","meanings":["English: variant of   Langton  ."]},{"name":"Lankton","meanings":["English: variant of   Langton  .","History: Thomas Lankton, born <i>c.</i> 1714 in Hartford County, CT, died 1783 in Litchfield County, CT, was a son of Joseph Langton."]},{"name":"Longton","meanings":["habitational name from Longton in Lancashire. The placename derives from Old English <i>lang</i> ‘long’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","variant of   Langton  .","English:"]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":6,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":15,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"John de Langton of Walton-Le-Dale was born in 1322, in England. He had at least 4 sons with Mrs. John de Langton. He died in 1360, in Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1322–1360":"1322–1360","1322–1387":"1322–1387","1329–Male":"1329–Surnud","1331–Male":"1331–Surnud","1340–1406":"1340–1406","–Male":"Surnud","1337":"1337","about 1329":"umbes 1329","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1387":"1387","1331":"1331","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","about 1331":"umbes 1331","1406":"1406","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, England":"Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gwynedd, Wales":"Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1322–1360":"1322–1360","1322–1387":"1322–1387","1329–Male":"1329–Kuollut","1331–Male":"1331–Kuollut","1340–1406":"1340–1406","–Male":"Kuollut","1337":"1337","about 1329":"noin 1329","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1387":"1387","1331":"1331","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","about 1331":"noin 1331","1406":"1406","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, England":"Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Walton-le-Dale, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Walton-le-Dale, Lancash